(19, 1, 2, 'Light leaking from a distant galaxy hints at a cosmic makeover’s origins', NULL, 'Harsh ultraviolet radiation suggests how hydrogen got ionized in the universe long ago', '<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">A leaky galaxy might be offering up clues about a vast cosmic makeover foisted on the universe during its youth.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Within about a billion years after the Big Bang, something stripped nearly all of the hydrogen atoms in the universe of their electrons. This &ldquo;reionization&rdquo; puzzles astronomers, who can&rsquo;t account for&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/article/faint-distant-galaxies-may-have-driven-early-universe-makeover\">all of the energy needed to make such a sweeping change</a>&nbsp;(<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">SN: 2/6/17</em>).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">A galaxy dubbed the Sunburst Arc might help. It appears to be blasting&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://science.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/science.aaw0978\">ionizing ultraviolet radiation through a small hole (or holes) carved out of the gas</a>&nbsp;that permeates the galaxy, researchers report in the Nov. 8&nbsp;<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">Science</em>. Similar channels in the earliest generation of galaxies could have provided an escape hatch for harsh light to zap intergalactic hydrogen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">While massive youthful stars can produce ionizing radiation, the light has trouble navigating the thickets of gas and dust within the host galaxy. &ldquo;Not all of it can get outside the galaxy, let alone reionize the intergalactic medium,&rdquo; says Brant Robertson, an astronomer at the University of California, Santa Cruz, who was not involved with the research. And yet, get out it must, given what happened to the cosmic inventory of hydrogen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Directly looking for ionizing radiation from the first galaxies is out of the question. Intervening gas clouds absorb that faint light long before it reaches Earth. &ldquo;The way to go about it is to look for [closer] analogs,&rdquo; says Joanna Bridge, an astronomer at the University of Louisville in Kentucky also not a part of this study. &ldquo;We look for galaxies that are similar &hellip; and gain an understanding of the physical processes that might have occurred.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: inherit; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; height: auto; max-width: 100%; color: #31313b;\"><img class=\"wp-image-958114\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; max-width: 100%; display: block; height: auto; width: 643px;\" src=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/110619_CC_reionization_inline_680.jpg\" alt=\"Suburst Arc galaxy\" />\r\n<figcaption style=\"margin: 0.5rem 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 0.75rem; line-height: 1.16667; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; display: inline-block;\"><span class=\"caption wp-caption-958114\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.5rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 0.75rem; line-height: 1.16667; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; display: block;\">Ionizing radiation blasts out of a single spot in the Sunburst Arc galaxy, made visible here using a special filter on the Hubble Space Telescope. The six spots of light are all from the same source, and are distorted and replicated thanks to the gravity of an intervening galaxy cluster (not shown).</span><span class=\"credit wp-credit-958114\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 0.625rem; line-height: 1.2; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; display: block; letter-spacing: 0.075em; text-transform: uppercase;\">T.E. RIVERA-THORSEN, HUBBLE SPACE TELESCOPE</span></figcaption>\r\n</figure>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Meet the Sunburst Arc, a galaxy in the small southern constellation Apus whose light takes nearly 11 billion years to reach Earth &mdash; far, but not quite as far as the galaxies responsible for reionization. Part of what makes the Sunburst Arc special is that it hides behind a much closer cluster of galaxies. The gravity from that cluster amplifies and smears the Sunburst Arc&rsquo;s light into an arc &mdash; hence its nickname &mdash; creating 12 distorted images of the galaxy smeared across the sky.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Two years ago, Rivera-Thorsen and colleagues noticed that a particular wavelength of ultraviolet light from this galaxy appeared&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/abs/2017/12/aa32173-17/aa32173-17.html\">to sneak out through small gaps in its hydrogen gas</a>, like water through a sieve. This light is not energetic enough to ionize hydrogen. But through those gaps, the team hypothesized, more energetic ionizing light might slip out as well.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">To test their idea, the team pointed the Hubble Space Telescope at the Sunburst Arc. In all 12 of the gravitationally distorted images, the researchers saw ultraviolet light capable of ionizing hydrogen blasting out of a small region within the galaxy. The source of the ultraviolet light coincides with a splotch of bright light seen in previous Hubble images, light that the team suspects radiates from a pocket of intense star formation no more than about 520 light-years across. The scientists think that the ionizing radiation from these young stars is using one or a few holes in the surrounding gas to escape into intergalactic space.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">&ldquo;This object is a unique lab for understanding the detailed way in which ionizing photons get out of a galaxy,&rdquo; Robertson says. The find is also reminiscent of another much closer galaxy, where a few years ago&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/article/nearby-galaxy-might-explain-what-tore-apart-universes-hydrogen\">astronomers reported a similar leak of ionizing light</a>&nbsp;(<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">SN: 10/10/14</em>).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Whether this actually is a missing piece in the reionization puzzle remains to be seen. &ldquo;In the part of the universe we studied, this is an atypical galaxy,&rdquo; Rivera-Thorsen says. Out of hundreds of thousands the team has looked at, no other galaxy appears to behave this way. Whether such open pathways in the gas were more common in earlier galaxies is unknown. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s still an open question,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Without this gravitational assist, &ldquo;we probably would not have noticed it,&rdquo; says Th&oslash;ger Emil Rivera-Thorsen, an astronomer at Stockholm University. &ldquo;It would have been just one more speck out of millions.&rdquo;<picture><source srcset=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/themes/sciencenews/client/src/images/cta-module@1x.jpg 1x,\r\n				https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/themes/sciencenews/client/src/images/cta-module@2x.jpg 2x\" media=\"(min-width: 768px)\" /><source srcset=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/themes/sciencenews/client/src/images/cta-module-sm@1x.jpg 1x,\r\n				https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/themes/sciencenews/client/src/images/cta-module-sm@2x.jpg 2x\" /></picture></p>', 'posts/December2019/l85IPzg1MHiDUjUC15OQ.jpg', 'light-leaking-from-a-distant-galaxy-hints-at-a-cosmic-makeover-s-origins', NULL, NULL, 'PUBLISHED', 0, '2019-11-08 03:15:42', '2019-12-08 21:08:22', 1),
(20, 1, 2, 'Voyager 2 reveals the dynamic, complex nature of the solar system’s edge', NULL, 'Data from two NASA spacecraft chart the boundary between the sun and the rest of the galaxy', '<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Humanity&rsquo;s second ambassador to interstellar space has reported back from the frontiers of the solar system &mdash; with the message that the border of the sun&rsquo;s territory is a complex and ever-changing place.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Late last year, NASA&rsquo;s Voyager 2 spacecraft&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/article/voyager-2-spacecraft-enters-interstellar-space\">broke through the heliopause</a>, the boundary where the solar wind gives way to the plasma that permeates the galaxy (<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">SN: 12/10/18)</em>. Six years earlier, its sister probe, Voyager 1,&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/article/last-voyager-1-slips-interstellar-space\">made its own heliopause crossing</a>&nbsp;(<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">SN: 9/12/13)</em>. Now, the combined results of these two journeys, published online November 4 in several papers in&nbsp;<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">Nature Astronomy</em>, offer the most detailed look yet at this largely unexplored region of space.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">These two robotic explorers &ldquo;are taking humankind to astonishing new places that 60 years ago we never imagined doing,&rdquo; says Gary Zank, a space physicist at the University of Alabama in Huntsville who was not involved with this research.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">The view outside Voyager 2&rsquo;s window changed on November 5, 2018, when the craft was about 17.8 billion kilometers from the sun &mdash; 119 times farther away than Earth &mdash; and the density of the surrounding plasma jumped&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"http://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-019-0918-5\">by about a factor of 20</a>. The steady stream of&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"http://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-019-0927-4\">low-energy atomic particles</a>&nbsp;from the sun dropped away, replaced by a barrage of far more&nbsp;<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: #176cab; text-decoration-line: none; transition: color 0.25s ease-in-out 0s; border-style: initial initial solid initial;\" href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-019-0928-3\">energetic particles</a>&nbsp;known as cosmic rays. These changes told researchers that Voyager 2 had left the sun&rsquo;s protective magnetic bubble, just over 41 years after beginning its sight-seeing expedition across the solar system.</p>\r\n<div class=\"wp-block-sciencenews-content-sidebar\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 1.5rem 1.5rem 1rem; border: 1px solid #176cab; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: inherit; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">\r\n<h3 style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 1.6rem; line-height: 1.35714; vertical-align: baseline;\">Cosmic protons</h3>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.75; vertical-align: baseline;\">As Voyager 2 crossed the heliopause &mdash; the boundary where the solar wind yields to interstellar plasma &mdash; it measured many more high-energy protons striking it per second. These particles, known as cosmic rays, originate far out in the galaxy and are usually deflected by the sun&rsquo;s magnetic field.</p>\r\n<h6 style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 1.15rem; line-height: 1.35714; vertical-align: baseline; text-align: center;\">Change in galactic proton rate as Voyager 2 crossed the heliopause</h6>\r\n<div class=\"image-desktop\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; height: auto; max-width: 100%;\"><img class=\"wp-image-958005\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; max-width: 100%; display: block; height: auto; width: 593px;\" src=\"https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/110419_cc_voyager2_inline1_desktop.png\" alt=\"proton rate graph\" />\r\n<figcaption style=\"margin: 0.5rem 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 0.75rem; line-height: 1.16667; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; display: inline-block;\"><span class=\"credit wp-credit-958005\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 0.625rem; line-height: 1.2; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; display: block; letter-spacing: 0.075em; text-transform: uppercase;\">S.M. KRIMIGIS&nbsp;<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">ET AL</em>/<em style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant: inherit; font-weight: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: inherit; line-height: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;\">NATURE ASTRONOMY</em>&nbsp;2019<br /><br /></span></figcaption>\r\n</figure>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.75rem; padding: 0px; border: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; font-variant-numeric: inherit; font-variant-east-asian: inherit; font-stretch: inherit; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; font-family: museo-sans, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #31313b;\">Voyager 1 had gotten there first, but Voyager 2 had an a</p>', 'posts/December2019/vxRxDWW907Kf62DQJQnP.jpg', 'voyager-2-reveals-the-dynamic-complex-nature-of-the-solar-system-s-edge', NULL, NULL, 'PUBLISHED', 1, '2019-11-08 03:17:53', '2019-12-10 17:37:43', 7);
